segments.text: in the year of 1969-70?
That's correct.
Okay.
Why did you decide to become involved in the anti-war movement at Southwest?
Well, I'd been involved in the anti-war movement in New York City, and when I arrived at Southwest, there was very little in the way of any war activities or organized activities going on.
So I, along with some other people, there was a coffee house on campus
that was sponsored by one of the church groups.

And that was sort of the focal point where we started having meetings of people who shared a similar interest in seeking to organize protests to speak out in a unified, organized manner against the war in Vietnam.
Okay, did you have more than one organization or was it one central organization there at the university?
At the time I got there, there wasn't any organization.
What we did was we
organized an ad hoc committee to organize anti-war activities and basically I along with a few other students formed a committee that began to organize and coordinate anti-war protests.
Okay and how many students did you have by the time you left involved in the movement?
I would say that by the time I left they were probably
some three to four hundred students that were actively involved.
And how many students were at Southwest at that time?
I think it was something like 12,000.
Okay, to you and to the people who formed the committee, what did the whole terminology of movement mean to you?
It meant a way of expressing our sentiment, our belief about

what was going on in Vietnam, that this country should not be participating in that kind of activity, and that we were not going to just passively sit back and allow the government to initiate and continue policies that we were very much opposed to.
There were points in terms of demonstrations at Southwest Texas that at one point probably involved as much as 10% of the student body.
So more people just joined with you?
More people joined.
The demonstration the evening that we were suspended from school in November probably had 2,000 people.

Many people who even did not agree with our views necessarily, or at least had felt some kinship with our views, decided this was a terrible way to treat students, people who were expressing themselves on the Ernie Ward position.
But it also brought out other students
who felt strongly about the war, had some misgivings about the war, and were finally speaking out against it, or at least engaging in some activity designed to protest our activity.
I think what it showed the administration was that many students did not like what was going on in Vietnam.
They had some misgivings.
It was difficult for a lot of students because a lot of the students there had grown up in very conservative rural Texas or small town Texas backgrounds.
And you just didn't question authority.
You didn't question administrators.
And this was something that people decided to do.
In the article that you have in the Texas magazine, I don't know if you remember that, you talk about your parents, they had the American dream.
And you also talk about...
how it was a time that you could question the things that you weren't supposed to question and just forbidden things that you shouldn't talk about.
How did your parents feel about what you were doing at school?
Well, they were very much upset about it.
They were concerned about it because they thought that somehow this wasn't right, that you don't question the authority of the government to do what it deems necessary in its governmental policies.
and it was very upsetting for them.
They grew up in a time when the government was, you just don't question the governmental authority.
Okay, what were the aims and goals of the organization itself?
The aims of the organization were to try and make students aware of what was going on in Vietnam and to try and give students a vehicle
to express their opposition to the war in Vietnam.
The goal was to try and get the government to change its policies in Vietnam.
It wasn't only, I think, to try and stop the draft, but certainly a lot of draft age people were involved at that time.
But it just wasn't merely that we were
going to be shipped off to war.
It was an overall expression that the policy that this government was pursuing was one that was unfair and unjust, and we wanted to try and change that.
And we believed that by voicing opposition, by mobilizing public opinion, that the government would have to change its policy.
And also, it was one of encouraging people our age to think before blindly going in and serving in the armed forces.
to pursue a policy that we thought was just inane.
Okay, do you feel that you reached any of these goals that the organization had?
I think we did.
In terms of the goals also, the goal was to provide a vehicle for expression among students and people in the community to express their feelings against the war.
I think that we
brought about a change in governmental policy.
I mean, we being San Marcos as part of what we viewed with the entire anti-war movement ultimately brought about a change.
The government could not pursue its policy the way it initially had planned because of the intense opposition.
I think as far as giving people a means of expressing their opposition, I think we really met that goal.
Because a lot of people who felt in opposition to the war
were inhibited because they weren't sure who else was opposed to it or how other people might react.
I mean, demonstrations at that point were a very new item in San Marcos.
It had just never happened.
And people had a means where people joined.
The first demonstration drew quite a bit of a crowd.
The second one, a much larger crowd.
There were probably about 1,000 people all together.
When I gave you that figure earlier, about 300 to 400, I'd say that's more of a core of people that were fairly actively involved and could be counted on to protest or join demonstrations.
But there were probably 1,000 people at the moratorium that was held in September, or rather October, the first one.
And then the one in November where we were suspended was even larger.
Okay, so my next question was, did you see any changes that took place in Southwest?
So obviously you did.
And you just went about getting these changes by having more and more students gain confidence?
Yeah, confidence that they could speak out, that their voice would have some effect.
By voicing what they felt, what their beliefs were, it would have some effect on the administration.
and the administration was forced to basically allow students their expression, their right of speech that the administration had tried to stifle before.
The suspension of us, the administration had to really back off when the Fifth Circuit allowed us to go back in school and finish the school year.
Okay, in this article it said that there were nine of you that were suspended.
That's correct, nine students.
Is that the nine leaders of the organization, quote-unquote leaders?
Right, quote.
It also says that later ruled that you were denied the student credit.
Right.
What happened was we were allowed to finish the school year.
The administration would not give us the actual credits we had earned until there was a final resolution of the case.
How long did that take?
That took about three more years.
So for three years, you were in limbo as to whether you had the credit for that year.
That's right.
OK, that kind of gets in the way of school.
Yeah, it essentially lost.
I mean, even at that point, I went ahead and graduated from City University of New York in June of 72.
And it wasn't until that fall that the US Supreme Court finally ruled.
So it almost was moot at that point.
But yeah, I just couldn't count on those points.
Right.
What was your draft status?
It was the college deferment, which I believe was 1S or 2S, which was just a college student.
I read in another article in a book, what part did you play in the class war, Daddy?
And they were talking about how he tried to get out of being put through the draft board by
being really underweight for being his height.
Did you know a lot of... Well, sure.
I knew of people who either tried to exaggerate any kind of physical defect or play on psychiatric or psychological problems.
There's a myriad of ways people seem to try and use, yeah.
There was a lot of that.
Did you have an underground newspaper?
Yes, we did.
It was called the Weather Report.
Do you have any copies of that?
I might, it's just been so long I'd have to look.
We also had the Purgatory Creek Press, which was actually published in 1969.
I'd have to look to see if I've got any copies.
Okay, if you had some would you send those to me?
Sure.
Or copies of the copies?
Yeah, sure.
Okay.
Were your views on the Vietnam War then versus now?
Well, I think in terms of my views then, I think I've expressed those to you.
Now, I still feel very much the same way.
It was a war that we should never have gotten involved in.
It caused tragic loss of American life, loss of Vietnamese life.
It created a whole class of Americans that came back from the war that were alienated, that had drug problems, mental problems.
It was just a great disaster for American youth.
I mean, still today there are lots of guys who went off to Vietnam and came back that have tremendous emotional as well as physical problems because of what happened there.
I mean, it was just a war that was not accepted.
People came home and you weren't considered a hero.
People just looked at you either as a killer or someone who didn't have enough courage, you know, to tell the government to go to hell.
And so I still feel the same way.
I think that we were pursuing basically a throwback to the imperialist policies or this colonial type policies that Americans had engaged in for many years.
And we just hadn't learned at that point that you just can't keep on doing this.
We met a different kind of military foe in Vietnam that could not be dealt with in conventional military ways.
Okay, you mentioned the fact that people looked at returning veterans as people who couldn't tell a government to go to hell.
Do you think that it had a lot to do with the Camelot that Kennedy portrayed at the beginning of the war?
Yeah, I think that has something to do with it.
I think that a lot of people weren't really sure
what was going on in Vietnam.

People still wanted to believe the government when the government was telling us that we were fighting, you know, to save these people from a communist bloodbath or from, you know, this communist slavery.
And Americans didn't have the means or the information to really question, and a lot of them didn't think about it.
And it wasn't

until a lot of the Vietnam veterans who came back from the war started complaining and questioning the policies that I think a lot more people started taking note that maybe what the government was telling us was not completely true.
And at that point I think there was a contingent of Vietnam vets.
Two of the people in our group, or at least one of them for sure, had been to Vietnam and had fought.
as a whole or at Southwest, was it based on issues or ideologies or both?
I'd say a combination of both.
You had, I think, a broad spectrum of people in terms of their ideology.
But the various issues about the war united people.
People felt this was not right, that we should not be in this war, and that it wasn't accomplishing any purpose.
that what we were doing was slaughtering a lot of people.
It was an endless, senseless loss of life.
How did the community of San Marcos react to the protesters at the school?
They were very hostile to the protesters, to the activities that were going on.
We were joined by some members of the community, some faculty members, and some people who lived in the community.
But for the most part, we were basically considered agitators, people who were just causing trouble, communists.
I was called Yankee agitator by a number of people.
They didn't like it at all.
They just saw this as a great, tragic, treasonous-type disruption of their community.
Growing up with the parents that you had and their American dream and

you believing this for years and years, and suddenly something coming up against that, and then someone calling you a communist and saying you're part of a conspiracy, that burst your bubble of what the American dream was about?
I wouldn't say it burst my bubble.
It made me realize that people that, you know, for a long time I had just incorrectly held to too much of an authoritarian type line that many people in this country had, that
you know, certain things were always right.
Whatever the government did was basically right.
And that, I learned at that point, or had in high school realized, come to realize that that was not always true.
I went to a high school where we were taught very much to question almost everything.
And I think that carried on to my years in college.
And as a result, I just
could no longer just hold to the same kind of ideology that my parents and relatives had.
Speaking of the community and how they reacted to you, did you ever face any physical danger yourself?
How did the police react to you in the establishment?
I faced a number of threats and there were a couple of close calls with vehicles in terms of that
seemed like, you know, I'd been almost hit a few times by cars.
There was a lot of threats, a lot of people in passing cars or just there were some phone calls and things like that.
There was quite a number of threats.
The police seemed indifferent to it.
We also had a demonstration that May or April

of 70, in which we almost had a physical confrontation that the school officials apparently chose to ignore, and we were able to diffuse it at the last moment by basically singing America the Beautiful and a few other things.
But there was, the school officials basically would not have minded if we'd have gotten beaten up.
Okay.
Also in that month, May 3rd and 4th of 1970,
There were four students killed and 10 wounded at Kent State by the Ohio National Guard.
What was the reaction in San Marcos and the Southwest about that?
We had a candlelight demonstration the night or two following the Kent State incident.
And there were well over 1,000 students that participated in that.
And we also had the demonstration I just described to you.
during the day in which the administration, there were a lot of cowboys around that were threatening us, and the administration basically just chose to ignore it.
And fortunately, though, there wasn't any violence.
Going on towards civil rights a little bit, did Southwest have any black students at that time?
Were they enrolled?
They had some.
They had a black club
a black political club.
The black student body was still very small.
Did they join you in the movement against Vietnam?
Some of the blacks did.
I'd say there were several blacks in the organization, but not a lot.
The blacks were somewhat uncertain in the sense that they had relatives who were telling them this was wrong, and they were just very uncertain about joining that kind of activity.
Were you involved in any part of this civil rights movement?
I had been involved in some marches in New York City in high school.
But as such, in San Marcos, it was essentially the anti-war movement.
Were there quite a few women involved in the movement?
Yeah, there were, I'd say, probably at least a third
And there was no problem with them being involved in that group?
It wasn't a sexist movement?
No, I would say no.
There are several organizations listed in this book, three.
The students working for a democratic society on campus, and
the Student Mobilization Committee.
Right.
Did those play an effect on your campus?
Were you involved in those?
Were they... Yeah, the Student Mobilization Committee was kind of a nationwide, or at least it operated out of Washington, or they had various chapters.
There was a chapter in Austin that we coordinate our activities with, because we did go to a major Washington demonstration through the Austin chapter.
in November or December of 69.
And that was basically a group that laid out strategies and set dates, national dates for activities.
So that was a group that was basically provided some leadership or some direction for local chapters around the country.
And we sort of saw our group as basically a chapter of the Student Mobilization Committee.
The Students for a Democratic Society, by 69, did not have a chapter in, they had one in Austin, but not in San Marcos.
They, at that time, they were beginning to fade out, weren't they?
Yeah, by 69 they had, because in May of 69, there were the demonstrations at Columbia by Mark Rudd, who was one of the leaders of the SDS.
That was sort of the beginning of the end where it started to fade out.
In the book, Who Spoke Up?, there was mention of bombings and arsons, arson cases sweeping the country at college campuses.
How did the people at Southwest feel about that type of violent action?
The administration was extremely paranoid about that happening.
There were not any instances of bombing or arson.
But the administration was extremely paranoid that that would happen.
And at one point, we had a demonstration where we marched on the administration building.
And we later found out that the administration had ordered records sealed and locked.
And they were afraid that we could go into the records and destroy things.
The administration was extremely paranoid.
All of our demonstrations were heavily marked by security, campus security, watching us.

In the same book, Kissinger is quoted as saying, Nixon never found the language of respect and compassion, which might have created a bridge at least to the more moderate elements of the anti-war movement, so that civil war conditions developed.
Did you at the time feel that you were involved in a civil war?
I wouldn't say, well, not a civil war in the sense that we had bullets flying between sides,
But it was a situation with a great deal of tension, a great deal of almost daily confrontation, a great deal of threats, extreme concern for one's safety.
And I felt that at any time, any of us could be harmed.
And there was a feeling of us against them.
The community was deeply divided, and we were in a much smaller segment.

And we were considered as somehow traitors, people who, you know, we were, a lot of the townspeople, a lot of people who'd never been to college, viewed us as having some kind of privilege to go to college, and how could we be doing this, meaning, you know, complaining to our elders about their policies when they'd given us college.
I mean, there was this kind of mentality.
How did the coverage of Vietnam on television
through the news and newsreels.
How did that affect the movement?
I think it had a very positive effect on the movement.
I thought television brought home the reality of what was going on in Vietnam.
People saw that it was gruesome, that it wasn't getting anywhere, and that it was not the way the administration wanted us to believe it was happening.
In your own terms, can you define hippie?
Yeah.

I suppose hippie was someone who was opposed to the establishment ways of doing things, the orthodox ways of doing things, and people who did various things to indicate their nonconformity by dress, clothing, use of drugs, hairstyles, shoe styles.
Someone who was out of, away from or
wanted to indicate that he did not go along with the mainstream.
But in 69, you had a lot of people who ideologically were hippies, in the sense that they did not conform or did not believe a lot of what the mainstream or a lot of what...
They didn't conform with the government's policies or believe or like the government's policies, but were still afraid to dress or act very differently.
So you were a hippie?
Yeah, I guess you'd have to say that.
But at the time, you were proud to wear that label.
Sure.
I mean, at that time, that didn't bother me, and it still doesn't.
I've been called an aging hippie.
Do you consider the movement a failure or success, and in what ways?
I consider it a success for a number of reasons.
One, it got people thinking.
It got people to think about their government's policies.
It got people to realize that they could question them.
And it got people to realize that by acting or by speaking out against what they felt was wrong or what was incorrect by the government, they could bring about a change.
And I think that was probably the greatest success.
I also think it was successful in the sense that it did bring about a change in the war.
cut down eventually on the slaughter that was going on in Vietnam, both of Americans and Vietnamese.
Do you feel that it failed in any way?
Well, I think the only, in the sense of failure, it was not able to get the government to change its position soon.
I feel like the failure is in the sense that it did not bring about a quicker change.
It did not get people, more people involved.
or convince more people to act on their beliefs.
I believe in 1969 there was a great deal of sentiment against the Vietnam War, and most people just basically held it back.
Okay, when do you believe that the movement ended, and why did it end?
I think it ended with the withdrawal of troops from Vietnam.
I thought at that point people felt like there was no longer a need
to protest about the government's policies because we weren't fighting in Vietnam.
And I thought it kind of came to an abrupt end then.

Although the movement tried to grab onto other issues, other policies, and keep itself going as a means of protesting or speaking out against what were considered unfair or unjust governmental policies.
But it's very hard to get people
involved and organized to get them out of the daily routine to really complain or protest about things that are going on that are not fair or just.
When did you decide and why did you decide to go to law school?
I had always wanted to be a lawyer even as a child, but I had somewhat questioned that in college.
I think that what I went through in 69 just

firmed up my resolve to go to law school because I realized that you could have so much more power and be so much more effective using the legal system than you could not being able to use that system.
Essentially, that's our society's way of fighting.
That's the sanctioned or approved way of fighting in this culture.
And I thought that if there was something I didn't believe in or something that I wanted to change that I felt was unfair, the courts were a way of doing it.
Are you satisfied with the role you played in the movement?
If you could, would you change anything?
If I could, I would have liked to have stayed.
Well, if I could have done anything differently, I would have liked to have been able to spend even more time trying to get more students involved, more people involved.
There was just a limit on time and facilities.
But I wish I could have gotten even more students involved.
That's all the questions I have right now.
Do you feel that there's anything I've left out that you consider?
I guess in terms of... One of the things that you might think about or that I think is important is how that affected people, you know, today.
I mean, how their activities in the movement affected them.
And I think that it had an effect.
It made people realize that they could do something about governmental policies they could band together and speak out.
And I think a lot of people who were involved in anti-war activities went on to things like the Sierra Club, environmental type activities, civil rights activities or women's issues.
that a lot of areas of the law, especially being a lawyer, I can see that a lot of areas of the law that just literally did not exist in the late 60s are now recognized by the courts.
And I think it changed the American legal scene in terms of people learned that they could do something in the system to fight.
Do you keep in touch with the other eight people that you were suspended with?
Yes, I do.
We get together.
We had a reunion in 79 after 10 years, and we'd see each other periodically.
Most of them still live around Austin.

And amazingly, even in 69, 79, we got together, the administration set up a policeman with a camera to take pictures surreptitiously, you know, but he was there on the top of the building taking pictures.
Yeah, I keep in touch.
We generally get together about once a year now, kind of reflect on what's going on and things like that.
In this article, you went back to San Marcos in 72 and you said the students were apathetic.
Was it hard for you to believe that after all that you'd worked for, you could come back so soon thereafter and have everything so different?
Yeah, it was hard to believe.
It was very frustrating because now, at that time, students could then vote in 72.
And because of the nature of San Marcos, the size and the size of the university, the students could have dictated the local government.
I mean, they could have elected a mayor, councilman, a lot.
And students just didn't care about it.
